        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <addressee>Rev. Mr. Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p>Dear Sir!</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">I shall answer to your note which<lb/> you appended to my letter as
                soon as my second<lb/> letter on the subject will be published.</p>
            <p>I am very sorry to read that an other <add>חזן</add> has<lb/> been elected in
                    <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>; I think the<lb/> affairs have not been
                managed in a proper way;<lb/> I know for sure that you have many friends in<lb/>
                <placeName>P.</placeName>; I hope this will not discourage you, and you<lb/> will
                after all not retire from public business,<lb/> and I am convinced <add>סוף הכבוד
                    לבוא</add>; the public<lb/> will and must acknowledge, that you were always<lb/>
                the banner-bearer of our Faith, and though it<lb/> is unpleasant to be set aside,
                still the conscious-<lb/>ness, that you did not deserve it, is a prompt<lb/>
                satisfaction.</p>
            <p>Peace and order have returned among the<lb/> Israelites of our City, and every past
                event is<lb/> almost entirely forgot; my Synagogue is again<lb/> so much visited,
                that many have to go of<lb/> because of want of room; while the other<lb/>
                Synagogues are very little visited but by their<lb/> own members; you see
                    <add>Hazan</add>. Go on<lb/> and care for nothing. The first day of <add>סוף
                    הכבוד לבוא</add><lb/> was devoted to service and the afternoon to the<lb/>
                examination of my happy little band, which<lb/> gave general satisfaction; I was
                delighted to see<lb/> how my former scholars, children of my severest<lb/> enemies,
                set there so attentively, and surrounded<lb/> me as affectionate as ever before. Let
                those be<lb/> grown up and <add>י"ט</add>. The members of our<lb/> choir gave a
                concert last night, which was<lb/> visited by a very numerous and respectable<lb/>
                audience, and every one was pleased by it.</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p>It is <sic>extremly</sic> delightful to hear children of 12<lb/> to 14 years sing the
                most difficult passages<lb/> with such a precision and readiness as they did.<lb/>
                Great praise is due to the Gentlemen of the choirs<lb/> they spare neither their
                time nor their money<lb/> to elevate the <sic>hebrew</sic> music; and I
                ardently<lb/> hope that the young people in other places<lb/> might follow this
                example.</p>
            <p>At a meeting of our Congregation <add>סוף הכבוד לבוא</add><lb/> it was passed, that
                the institution of a <add>כאנשי אמת</add><lb/> be abolished in this Congregation;
                all singing<lb/> to be done by the choir, according to <persName>Sulzer's</persName>,<lb/>
                <persName>Naumburger's</persName> or other <sic>hebrew</sic> music; the prayers<lb/>
                to be read in the common oral tunes by the<lb/> Rabbi of the Congregation, who has
                to stand<lb/>
                <add>חזן</add>; the Thorah to be read in a modern<lb/> tune of reading by one
                appointed to it.</p>
            <p>I saw, that my friend <persName>Kalisch</persName> has thrown some<lb/> sparks of his
                immense erudition before the critical<lb/> world. He will repent it by the by, I am
                sure of it,<lb/> but still I like to see him caught in that fatal<lb/> net. Who is
                    <persName>Miss L. R. T.</persName>? <sic>a</sic> remarkable<lb/> woman indeed; I
                should like to know some<lb/> more about her. Where lives <persName>Mrs. R.
                    H.</persName>?<lb/> I wish to enter in a <sic>privat</sic> correspondence
                with<lb/> both of them, and you would oblige me giving<lb/> me their directions.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Wishing you <add>פניו כלפי העם</add> and God's blessing.</p>
            <p rend="indent(2)">I remain <sic>truely</sic></p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">yours</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">
                <persName role="author">Wise</persName>
            </p>
            <p>
                <add>שמחת יום טוב</add>
            </p>
            <pb n="4"/>
            <p>
                <addressee>Rev. Mr. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
